  <task workspace="10%">
    <p>
      Show that <m>\vec{M_1} + \vec{M_2} + \vec{M_3} = 0</m>. (<em>Hint.</em>
      Use part<nbsp /><xref ref="p_cyclic" />.)
    </p>
  </task>

  <task workspace="10%">
    <p>
      To show that the point <m>P</m> exists
      (as the common intersection of
      the <m>\vec{M_i}</m>),
      show that
      <me>
        \vec{A} + \frac{2}{3} \vec{M_3} = \frac{2}{3} \vec{M_2} = \lt fillin characters="10"/>
      </me>
    </p>
  </task>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If you have time,
        try to devise a vector proof of Euclid's result presented at the beginning of the workshop.
        Recall that a parallelogram is a four-sided figure whose opposite sides are parallel.<fn>It is a theorem, not part of the definition, that each pair of parallel sides has a common length.</fn></p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>

